slidetranscripts.Text:
Welcome to the HCC Early Alert Program presentation.

This presentation has sound. To adjust the volume or mute the sound, click on the speaker icon on the bottom left of the screen and drag the slider up or down.

At any time throughout this presentation, you can click on any of the titles in the table of contents to the right to jump to a specific slide.

You can also click on the Transcript tab to the right of the Contents tab to view the written text of the narration.

In this module you will learn about the Early Alert Program, or Starfish, the programs goals, tutorials, tips and resources to help you navigate through the program.

Click the Next arrow at the bottom of the screen to begin.

If this is your first time taking this presentation, click the New Users button to begin.

If you are returning to this guide for reference, click on the buttons to the right to jump to a specific slide.

Amy: HCC Early Alert or Starfish is an early warning program that allows instructors to provide feedback and support to their students when they need it the most.

Click the starfish to see how the HCC Early Alert program works.

The program is connected to Canvas and can be easily accessed by both faculty and students.

Student concerns and/or praise can be manually flagged when observed or during periodic progress surveys each main semester.

Student advisors are informed of the flags that were raised, follow-up with the students and then clear the flags.

Student advisors close the loop through notes sent to faculty when progress and/or contact is made with the students.

Click Next to continue.

Click on each of the students below to view the goals of the Early Alert Program.

Then click Next to continue.

1. Increase student persistence and completion via Early Alerts

2. Promote student-faculty engagement

3. Identify students who are at risk early on in the semester

4. Assist students in understanding how their behaviors and actions affect their grades and performance

5. Assess students needs and refer them to the appropriate resources if needed

6. Streamline communication between students, faculty and campus resources

There are two ways to access the HCC Early Alert program.

You can access the Early Alert program through Canvas.

Go to your Canvas course page and click Early Alert from the menu on the left.

Click Next to view the other way to access the HCC Early Alert program.

You can also use the URL Login to access the HCC Early Alert program.

The Early Alert program does not work well on Internet Explorer so it is recommended that you use the latest version of Firefox, Google Chrome or Safari.

Go to https://howardcc.edu/starfish

Then enter your Username. This is your first initial, the first seven characters of your last name and the last four digits of your colleague ID number.

Enter your Password. This is the same password you use to access computers at HCC and your HCC email.

Then click Login.

Click Login here to continue.

Amy: Click the link to view a video demonstration of how to set up your profile.

Click on your name at the top right side of the page.

Enter a phone number where you can be reached.

Then upload a photo to personalize your page. To do this: Select the Upload Photo link. Browse for a photo from your files. The recommended file formats are JPEG, GIF and PNG. Then, click the Upload Now button.

You can also provide a general overview of your office hours or a biography. When youre finished, click Save.

Note that some of your profile information is imported from Colleague.

Click Next to continue.

Click on the images on the left to learn more about flags and kudos.

Then click Next to continue.

Flags are Early Alerts to help keep students on track.

Flags should be raised when instructors see the following signs:

Poor Attendance

Late or Missing Assignments

Low Academic Performance

Student is in danger of failing

Kudos are positive affirmations of a job well done.

Kudos should be given when instructors see the following signs:

Academic Improvement

Outstanding work

Amy: Click on each of the faculty members below to view a tip from each of them.

Then click Next to continue.

Feel free to contact the Completion Services staff (443-518-1320) if you have any concerns or questions. We want to work together to help the students be successful and achieve their academic goals.

Make time in the first week of classes to have your students access the Starfish/Early Alert tab on their canvas page to set up their profile.

Encourage students to sign up for the SMS text option on their profile page to receive notifications through their phones.

Alert your students when you submit your flags and kudos. Note your office hours or times you may be available to discuss the flags/concerns with your students.

Include the HCC Early Alert Syllabus and HCC Early Alert Video Tutorial on your Canvas page. These will be sent to you through email.

Have students log on to their HCC email account. If they are having trouble with their password or logging in, have them call the Help Desk at 443-518-4444 or use password services on the website.

Stress that all communication from the college comes to this account and should be checked routinely.

Encourage students to utilize campus resources and support. There is a multitude of services available and they are free! See Academic and Student Resources in the resources tab.

Amy: Raising a flag, manually or via a progress survey on a student will be captured in the students Starfish Record.

It will produce an automatic email to the student regarding the flag and alert the students advisor who will then reach out to the student and clear the flag.

To manually raise a flag, click the My Students tab.

Then click the check box next to the student for whom you want to raise the flag.

Click the Raise Flag button. This will open a new window where you will provide information about the flag.

Click next to view the next steps.

In the new window, select the appropriate flag in the Tracking Item drop down menu.

Your choices include:

Poor attendance

Late or missing assignments

Low academic performance, and

Student in danger of failing.

In the comments section, make some comments about why the tracking item is being created. This is optional but it is recommended in order to provide more information about the student so that the appropriate actions can be taken.

Finally, click save.

Click Next to continue or click Back to view steps 1-3 again.

Progress surveys are automatic periodic requests for faculty to evaluate students progress and note concerns or praise. Progress Surveys allow faculty to view each of their class roster(s) and select flags or kudos easily for their students.

HCC Early Alert designates 3 progress surveys per semester. Click the numbers below to view when each of these surveys occur.

Then click Next to continue.

First Survey or Launch:

Usually begins the 2nd or 3rd week of class.

Focus on attendance concerns or lack of log in for online courses

Second Survey or Launch:

Usually begins the 5th week of class.

Focus on low academic performance and missing/late assignments.

Third Survey or Launch:

Usually begins in the later part of the semester before the designated last day to withdraw.

Focus on students in danger of failing.

Amy: Click the links to view a sample progress survey or to view a video demonstration of the process of completing a progress survey.

To complete a progress survey:

1. Navigate to the Starfish Home page.

2. Click on Outstanding Progress Surveys located below Systems Announcement.

3. Click on the title of the course for which you would like to complete the survey. Your class roster for the class will appear.

4. Then click the buttons to the right of the students names to raise a concern or kudo. Note that the default response No Concerns is automatically selected.

5. You can choose to add a note with more details about the concern. When you click a flag on the student, a notepad/pen icon will appear next to the students name. Click on this icon to enter your comments.

6. When finished, click Submit to save the survey responses.

Click Next to continue.

The learning assistance center is located in RCF 340. You can contact them by dialing x1320.

The learning assistance center holds study skills workshops and has both scheduled and drop-in tutoring available for current students.

There is also a drop-in write room and online writing assistance available.

The learning assistance center also holds math reviews and has video tutorials to help students.

Adaptive lab equipment for students with disabilities is available.

Completion staff are also available to meet with students and have flexible hours including nights and weekends.

Click Next to continue.

Click the pictures to view other resource centers and labs.

Then click Next to continue.

The ESL Pronunciation Lab is located in DH 210.

It is available for HCC students enrolled in any credit class and for non-native speakers

The ESL Pronunciation Lab provides individualized practice in Pronunciation, Presentation Skills, Academic Discussion Skills, and Interview Skills.

The Composition & Literature Center (CLC) is located in DH 210 and provides individualized instruction for all HCC students enrolled in an English course.

Tutoring in the CLC is offered on a walk-in basis

The Math Center (MAC) is located in Hickory Ridge 230.

It is open to all HCC students currently enrolled in a Mathematics class

Computer software is available for all math courses and free tutoring is offered by faculty and student tutors

The Open Accounting Lab is located in DH 301 and is manned by instructors and peer leaders.

The Open Accounting Lab allows students to study for exams alone or with other students and provides help with homework or specific problems or concepts.

Instructors and/or peer mentors are available to answer questions for students.

Thank you for completing this presentation on the HCC Early Alert program.

For any questions or problems you may have with the Early Alert program, please contact Lynn Voyton at x4231 or Melodie Gale at x4687.

For questions about Resources and Support for students, contact our Completion Staff located in RCF 340 at 443-518-1320.

Click the Exit button to end this presentation or click the Home button to return to the quick navigation slide. Thank you!
